CREATING A TENSOR 

   - empty allocates memory of desired size and dont assign any value
   - zeroes assign value zero 
   - ones assign value 1
   - rand assign random value from 0-1
   - manual_seed( a no is assigned to this seed here eg 100) permanently assigns the random value that .rand creates afterwards
   - tensor to manually give
   - arange(int :start , int :end , int :jump)
   - linspace(int :start , int :end , int :linear spacing)
   - eye(n) to create a identity matrix of n*n
   - full((size) , all no are equal to)

TENSOR SHAPE (assume x is the tensor already defined)

   - x.shape tells the shape
   - torch.empty_like(x) creates a random tensor of size x
   - zeroes_like
   - ones_like
   - rand_like - this will NOT work as sometimes the values of x can be all integer but rand gives float 


TENSOR DATATYPE

   -x.dtype tell the datatype 
